top.value: A Danish project group in Ung Mosaik (UM) has due to previous trips to Nakuru, Kenya and contact with the potential partner, The Free Pentecostal Fellowship in Kenya Youth (FPFK Youth), a desire to determine whether a formalized partnership between the two organizations can be established The project group has seen a great need of support and help in the area of Nakuru where FPFK Youth headquarters is located FPFK Youth?s initiative to empower and educate the local youth has sparked an interest in the Danish group to support this objective in order to have an even greater impact and sustainability FPFK Youth has a vision to build up capacity in at-risk youth to become active agents in their own lives, instead of being passive victims of poverty and injustice and to participate actively in their local communities Through activities, workshops and meetings during a Partner Identification trip our goal is to determine if a future sustainable partnership is possible The dream scenario is to lay the ground of a fruitful partnership that supports and empowers the leaders of FPFK Youth to have a greater impact in their community

After 4 years of cooperation, we want to discuss new aspects of our partnership.  Due to corona we want to see if we could find a way to arrange the local forum day from our Partnership Project. We still think this activity is important for our partnership. We want to involve the elected officials of Aalborg and F?s to create other channels of collaboration between the various actors of the two cities.  Another aspect of our partnership is democracy. Both AY and CSworks daily with democracy and the involment of youngpeople in community life and the promotion of youth participation through participatory democracy mechanisms and citizen participation. For this project, we want to involve the peer education group ?Aalborg Youth council? in our partnership so the peer education approach can combine the peer education group ?Sexualisterne? with the ?Youth council in Aalborg and the local youth council in COS. We want to train and support its organs and the use of peer education as a means of training and sensitizing young people for effective participation in local governance.

After 5 years of cooperation and a newly finished partnership project, our aim is to use this opportunity to reflect upon the lessons learned this far and together define and match our visions and hopes for the future of our partnership. This will be done through discussions and workshops between the members of the three organisations leading up to the development of a new partnership strategy and agreement. In addition, we would like to secure a basis for our future work, and improve the conditions for this, by having workshops in communication and handovers, building up the capacity in each organisations to ensure the strength and sustainability of the IMUNZI partnership.

A project group in Ung Mosaik has due to previous trips to Lebanon and contact with the potential partner, Eagles in Christ (ECY), a desire to determine whether a formalized partnership between the two organizations can be established The project group has seen a great need of support and help in the suburb of Beirut where ECY is located, which is an area with a huge influx of Syrian refugees ECY?s initiative to empower and educate the local youth has sparked an interest in the Danish group to support this objective in order to have an even greater impact and sustainability ECY has a vision to build up capacity in at-risk youth to become active agents in their own lives, instead of being passive victims of war and injustice and to participate actively in their local communities Through activities, workshops and meetings during a partner identification trip our goal is to determine if a future sustainable partnership is possible The dream scenario is to lay the ground of a fruitful partnership that supports and empowers the leaders in ECY to have a greater impact on the Syrian and Lebanese youth at risk

Ashipti Denmark works toward educating young people and citizens of the immense strain Non-Commutable-Diseases have on society, public health care, and most importantly on individuals. With our previous experience in working with partnerships and on NCD prevention in Uganda, we hope to start a new partnership in Ghana. Our plan is to conduct a Partnership-Identification, in-volving a visit in Ghana for approximately  10 days where we will have meetings and workshops with the organisation Ghana FGMSA that we have been in contact with as well as other relevant stakeholders to get a proper understanding of the context and identify other possibilities of future partnerships.   The main goal is to find out if Ashipti Denmark and Ghana FGMSA match in regard to common values, goals and working methods and if so, find a common ground to start a new partnership working with NDC prevention in Ghana since NCDs is an increasing problem in Ghana, this would preferably be in the form of a preparatory study or pilot project. The focus on a new project be-sides NCDs, would be capacity building with both partners involved.

Ashipti works toward educating young people and the general population about the immense strain that Non-Communicable-Diseases (NCDs) have on society, public health care, and most important-ly on individuals. With our previous experience in working with partnerships and on NCD prevention in Uganda, we hope to start a new partnership in Ghana. Our plan is to conduct a partner-ID, in-volving a visit in Ghana for approximately 12 days where we will have meetings and workshops with the organizations Diabetes Youth Care (DYC) and Youth Advocates Ghana (YAG) that we have been in contact with, as well as other relevant stakeholders, in order to get a proper understanding of the context and identify other possibilities of future partnerships.   	The main goal is to find out if Ashipti and DYC or YAG (or maybe other organizations) is a match in regard to common values, goals and working methods and if so, find a common ground to start a new partnership working with NDC prevention in Ghana, since NCDs are an increasing problem there. This project would preferably be in the form of a preparatory study followed by a pilot pro-ject. The focus of a new project besides NCDs, will be capacity building with both partners involved.

As the first partnership project between DRCY and MRCS ended this year this preparatory study will seek to gather all lessons learned in order to get a full overview of how to best continue with a new partnership project. The previous partnership focused on strengthening youth in the districts of Mwanza, Mangochi and Chikwawa through skill-development and community-based youth activities as well as capacity-building of local and national youth structures. It was implemented as a parallel project to the youth component of the MRCS Community Resilience Project (ComRep), supported by the Danish Red Cross (DRC). MRCS and DRC has agreed to initiate a new phase of ComRep running from 2020-2023, as it has shown great impact including great results regarding the empowerment of the youth in both MRCS and in the targeted districts.  The purpose of this study is therefore to tie together the recently ended partnership with a new, by ensuring that all details are discussed to safeguard a close integration with the new ComRep and a close involvement of MRCS. The study will prioritise workshops with core volunteers and staff from MRCS. This application has been developed in a participatory process including volunteers from the DRCY YPA network and two board members from the MRCS Youth who took part in the DRCY AGM in October 2019 and with inputs from the DRCY secretary.

Based on findings from a preparatory study in August 2019, the Danish Red Cross Youth (DRCY) and Kenya Red Cross Society (KRCS) now wish to initiate a joint pilot project Youth in an existing Urban Resilience (UR) program between the KRCS and Danish Red Cross (DRC) have a strong desire to give back to their communities and create positive change However, they lack the necessary tools and support for creating initiatives that target youth as beneficiaries Thus, DRCY will share core competencies and experience and support youth volunteers in identifying areas where they can create a positive impact for other youth Together, DRCY- and KRCS volunteers will find valuable ways for youth volunteers to help build resilience with other youth This will strengthen not only youth themselves but also the local community in question and the KRCS at large
